# Random Seed Management Standards

This document defines standards for seed management across libraries, reproducibility verification, and multi-library consistency in computational research.

---

## Core Principle: All Randomness Must Be Controllable

Every source of randomness in the pipeline -- from data shuffling to weight initialization to dropout -- must be seeded from a single, recorded master seed. Running the same code with the same seed must produce the same results (within documented tolerance).

---

## Master Seed Protocol

### Single Entry Point

```python
import os
import random

import numpy as np

MASTER_SEED = int(os.environ.get("EXPERIMENT_SEED", "42"))


def seed_everything(seed: int = MASTER_SEED) -> None:
    """Seed all random number generators from a single master seed."""
    random.seed(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)

    try:
        import torch
        torch.manual_seed(seed)
        torch.cuda.manual_seed_all(seed)
        torch.backends.cudnn.deterministic = True
        torch.backends.cudnn.benchmark = False
    except ImportError:
        pass

    try:
        import tensorflow as tf
        tf.random.set_seed(seed)
    except ImportError:
        pass

    os.environ["PYTHONHASHSEED"] = str(seed)
```

### Seed Rules

- [ ] Master seed is set once at program start, before any random operation
- [ ] Master seed is recorded in experiment metadata and results
- [ ] Derived seeds (for different components) are computed deterministically from master seed
- [ ] Seed is passed via environment variable or config file (not hard-coded)

